<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTING TARGET HOLLYWWOD; 
</P>
<P>
THE ETHICS OF EXPOSING CELEBRITIES' SEXUAL ORIENTATIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
What we as gay people are fighting is invisibility. Recently, ABC bowed to 
pressure from its sponsors (including Pillsbury and Toys 'R' Us) and will not 
rerun the episode of "thirtysomething" that includes a humanly dimensioned gay 
character. 
</P>
<P>
This is the kind of attempt at rendering us invisible that created a need for 
outing in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
Ultimately, perhaps just getting people to recognize that a lot of the people 
around them, including their movie, TV and sports idols might be gay will help 
to break down prejudices and we can all get on with the important things, like 
fighting AIDS instead of each other. 
</P>
<P>
THOMAS SIEGEL 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
