<P>
Photo, For two decades after the Berlin Wall's erection in 1961, the 
15-foot-high barrier stood gray and forbidding, marked only by guard towers. 
But in the early 1980s, a group of artists including Keith Haring and Harald 
Nageli (the "Zurich Sprayer") began to attack the featureless concrete. Soon 
the 102-mile-long wall was an enormous public canvas, covered with any and all 
means of expression: spray paint, mosaics, even lipstick. German artist Hermann 
Waldenberg's photos of this figurative storming of the barrier, taken between 
1984 and the Wall's physical dismantling last year, are collected in "The 
Berlin Wall" (Abbeville Press: $19.95, paper). 
</P>
