<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE; 
</P>
<P>
NURSING HOME IS CLOSED BY OFFICIALS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The San Jose health department has closed a nursing home after a five-month 
surveillance revealed serious deficiencies in the treatment of 62 elderly 
patients, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
Carla Framiglio, district administrator for the health department, said she 
recommended closing the 160-bed Evergreen Healthcare after receiving calls from 
vendors who said they would no longer provide services to the home. Framiglio 
said changes in patients' conditions were not reported to doctors, errors 
occurred in giving patients medicine and records lacked proper documentation. 
She said her staff had issued 21 citations -- seven for serious deficiencies -- 
during Evergreen Healthcare's first year of operation. Officials have placed 40 
Evergreen residents and were still trying to locate the relatives of the 
others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
