</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
AMERICA'S HOUSING: HOME PRICES TO RISE IN '90S, STUDY SAYS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CATHERINE COLLINS, Collins, a veteran real estate reporter, writes from 
Washington on housing-related issues. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Which of the following statements is true? 
</P>
<P>
1 -- "Real housing prices may well reach levels lower than those experienced at 
any time in the past 40 years." 
</P>
<P>
2 -- "Today's homeowners have little reason to worry. Over time, home prices 
tend to rise at or above the general rate of inflation making housing a solid 
investment and key component in the financial security of the current and 
future generations of elderly Americans." 
</P>
<P>
Both are true, according to two Harvard University studies of the housing 
market. 
</P>
<P>
only households with heads aged 25 and over. Due to small sample size, there is 
no separate category for Hispanics. 
</P>
<P>
SOURCE: Federal Reserve Board, 1986 Survey of Consumer Finance, and "The State 
of the Nation's Housing 1990." 
</P>
</TEXT>
